Synchronous vs Asynchronous Programming in JavaScript:

1. Synchronous Programming: In this model, tasks are executed one by one in a linear sequence. The control flow is strictly determined by the order of task execution. If one task takes more time to complete (like fetching data from a server), all other tasks have to wait for it to finish before they can start executing. This results in blocking behavior where an operation has to be completed before another starts, thus limiting performance and speed.
   ```javascript
    console.log("Starting execution"); // Task 1 - Syncronous Execution

    function taskOne(callback){
        setTimeout(() => {
            callback('Task one completed');
        }, 500);
    }

    taskOne((result) => {        
        console.log("Result: ", result); // Task 2 - Syncronous Execution
    });
   ```
    In the above example, we have two tasks, each being executed synchronously and blocking the execution of other tasks while they are running.

2. Asynchronous Programming: This model allows JavaScript to execute multiple tasks concurrently without any need for them to be executed in a specific order. Here, JavaScript continues with the next task immediately after it has started the current one; it doesn't wait until the previous task finishes before starting on the new task. 
   ```javascript
    console.log("Starting execution"); // Task 1 - Asynchronous Execution

    function asyncTaskOne(){
        setTimeout(() => {
            console.log('Async Task one completed');
        }, 500);
    }

    asyncTaskOne();
   ```
    In the above example, we have an asynchronous task that runs independently of any other tasks. JavaScript doesn't wait for it to finish and continues with the next lines of code after invoking this function.

